  }, "Two's Complement binary for Negative Integers:")), mdx("blockquote", null, mdx("p", {
    parentName: "blockquote"
  }, "Negative numbers are written with a leading one instead of a leading zero. So if you are using only 8 bits for your twos-complement numbers, then you treat patterns from \"00000000\" to \"01111111\" as the whole numbers from 0 to 127, and reserve \"1xxxxxxx\" for writing negative numbers. A negative number, -x, is written using the bit pattern for (x-1) with all of the bits complemented (switched from 1 to 0 or 0 to 1). So -1 is complement(1 - 1) = complement(0) = \"11111111\", and -10 is complement(10 - 1) = complement(9) = complement(\"00001001\") = \"11110110\". This means that negative numbers go all the way down to -128 (\"10000000\").")), mdx("blockquote", null, mdx("p", {
